<subSubSection id="9DD356D8D39259D8310EF14C35E79D85" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="EFBA295057D4B6BF01A5611B9E0A64A3" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E519BB5F0B246168613D30377D5BC067" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Length 5-8 mm. The species differs from other species of the genus by its completely violet-blue (female) or black-green to black-blue (male) body, and a wide and shallow apical notch on T3. The scapal basin is also higher and dorsally deeply angled. Exceptionally small and worn specimens can be confused with 
<taxonomicName id="CCE3A20FC5DCAD90B9F437C24280AD32" authority="Panzer, 1801" authorityName="Panzer" authorityYear="1801" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Omalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Omalus puncticollis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="puncticollis">Omalus puncticollis</taxonomicName>
(or 
<taxonomicName id="D5EF01D09E63F060E730184F75815D6D" authority="Panzer, 1801" authorityName="Panzer" authorityYear="1801" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Omalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Omalus aeneus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aeneus">Omalus aeneus</taxonomicName>
), but the mesopleuron of 
<taxonomicName id="A185974B9A46B94FB169F527A50E1C8F" authority="Ashmead, 1902" authorityName="Ashmead" authorityYear="1902" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Pseudomalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pseudomalus violaceus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="violaceus">Pseudomalus violaceus</taxonomicName>
always strongly projects ventrally (as in Fig. 28) and the mesoscutum has large punctures, which are clumped postero-medially (as in Fig. 27).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A38367BB4CD3D1C2875C2CFA8C110E18" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="37D28740B1DC132DC4D05141A396B0AF" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="78D1E56606431E45E50266E7BEB57140" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Denmark, Estonia, Finland, Latvia, Lithuania, Norway, Sweden. Relatively rare. - Trans-Palearctic (?). Europe, Middle East, Siberia, Manchuria (
<bibRefCitation id="66C39154CF4EF12DE4B9B1C3CA15A81E" author="Linsenmaier, W" journalOrPublisher="Veroeffentlichungen aus dem Natur-Museum Luzern" pageId="95" pageNumber="96" pagination="1 - 139" title="Die Goldwespen der Schweiz." volume="9" year="1997">Linsenmaier 1997</bibRefCitation>
). Eastern records could be related to 
<taxonomicName id="5CC9DA215D2A8CCCDFBA345776EB8DE2" authority="Ashmead, 1902" authorityName="Ashmead" authorityYear="1902" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Pseudomalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pseudomalus bergi" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bergi">Pseudomalus bergi</taxonomicName>
Semenov, 1932 (
<bibRefCitation id="3D702D130331EB3C2322D6B195875F04" author="Rosa, P" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="98" pageNumber="99" pagination="1 - 128" title="An annotated checklist of the chrysidid wasps (Hymenoptera, Chrysididae) from China." url="10.3897/zookeys.455.6557" volume="455" year="2014">Rosa et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
) or other similar central Asiatic species, e.g. 
<taxonomicName id="AAE84A732512CB3961EE12085E26BB9F" authority="Ashmead, 1902" authorityName="Ashmead" authorityYear="1902" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Pseudomalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pseudomalus bogojavlenskii" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bogojavlenskii">Pseudomalus bogojavlenskii</taxonomicName>
Semenov, 1932 or 
<taxonomicName id="17B935CADAA20E11C2C7291EFA7AB6FA" authority="Ashmead, 1902" authorityName="Ashmead" authorityYear="1902" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Pseudomalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pseudomalus saturatus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="saturatus">Pseudomalus saturatus</taxonomicName>
Semenov, 1932.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="585E4671C044AB48A19C6224E5E43747" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="biology">
<paragraph id="709104C94529E921D9E1777E6846B0C4" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3149E60495224D58153A66544E31B476" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
Habitat: forest margins and clearings. Often found on leaves of sun-exposed deciduous trees and bushes. Flight period: June to August. Adults are attracted to honeydew of aphids (
<bibRefCitation id="5CF99179137B389BB259D3EE55827EA7" author="Gauss, R" journalOrPublisher="Mitteilungen des Badischen Landesvereins fuer Naturkunde und Naturschutz, Neue Folge" pageId="93" pageNumber="94" pagination="361 - 371" title="Varietaeten, Abnormitaten und Raritaten bei Hautflueglern (HymenopteraAculeata), gleichzeitig dritter Nachtrag zur Hautflueglerfauna im badischen Raum." volume="14" year="1987">Gauss 1987</bibRefCitation>
). Host: 
<taxonomicName id="DB7F68F13B38B3911C632988331EBCA2" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Pemphredon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pemphredon lugubris" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lugubris">Pemphredon lugubris</taxonomicName>
(Fabricius), more rarely also 
<taxonomicName id="27C3C634F6A9283F9D9B3B7639E8E7DB" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Passaloecus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Passaloecus corniger" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="corniger">Passaloecus corniger</taxonomicName>
Shuckard and 
<taxonomicName id="42183038F7E43486CFDA133E9D71E0F1" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Passaloecus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Passaloecus eremita" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eremita">Passaloecus eremita</taxonomicName>
Kohl (
<taxonomicName id="9F92BB83449B8667A72D5AF32CECE384" family="Crabronidae" lsidName="" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="family">Crabronidae</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="C52B2AE4548E4EE4BDBBA2E3039B9F04" author="Nielsen, IC" journalOrPublisher="Videnskabelige Meddelelser fra den naturhistoriske Forening i Kjobenhavn for" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" pagination="255 - 280" title="Biologiske Studier over Gravehvepse." volume="1900" year="1900">Nielsen 1900</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="E73C837D20CE968998B1F730617C9A90" author="Morgan, D" journalOrPublisher="Royal Entomological Society of London, London" pageId="96" pageNumber="97" title="Cuckoo-wasps, Hymenoptera, Chrysididae. Handbooks for the Identification of British Insects, Vol. 6, Part 5." year="1984">Morgan 1984</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="3F18421D24E60BE478742F3436A7215D" author="Gathmann, A" journalOrPublisher="Naturschutz und Landschaftspflege Baden-Wuerttemberg" pageId="93" pageNumber="94" pagination="277 - 305" title="Landschafts-Bewertung mit Bienen und Wespen in Nisthilfen: Artenspectrum, Interactionen und Bestimmungschluessel." volume="73" year="1999">Gathmann and Tscharntke 1999</bibRefCitation>
, our own obs.). Host records of other species (e.g. 
<taxonomicName id="B1FEAD2A50AEFCBEFC1C86FB5017A779" class="Insecta" family="Crabronidae" genus="Trypoxylon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Trypoxylon" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Trypoxylon</taxonomicName>
Latreille) are doubtful, because of their deviant biology compared to other hosts. In Finland, the species has been reared from an old gall of 
<taxonomicName id="C210F1D3CB5586926074F59A1E22ED89" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Saperda" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Saperda populnea" order="Coleoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="populnea">Saperda populnea</taxonomicName>
(Linnaeus) (
<taxonomicName id="D34662205703076F0B879F2E35F8A156" family="Cerambycidae" lsidName="" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" rank="family">Cerambycidae</taxonomicName>
) on a 
<taxonomicName id="035444515A4E44077E4D43C55383A336" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Salicaceae" genus="Populus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Populus" order="Malpighiales" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Populus</taxonomicName>
branch (M. Pentinsaari pers. obs.) and a rotten 
<taxonomicName id="DB917B41309B88771EDACB49D39FBF28" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Betulaceae" genus="Alnus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Alnus" order="Fagales" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Alnus</taxonomicName>
stump containing host nests.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
